videos.title: 7'2 Yang Hansen Is The Chinese Nikola Jokic!
videos.description:
20-year old 7'2 Yang Hansen is the Chinese version of Nikola Jokic, who plays exactly like the younger version of Nikola Jokic. Yang Hansen was selected by the Memphis Grizzlies as the 16th pick of the 2025 NBA draft but then later traded to the Portland Trail Blazers. Yang Hansen is the 9th Chinese player to be drafted to the NBA since Yi Jianlian and Yao Ming.

â–¶ï¸ Yang Hansen is a Chinese professional basketball player for the Portland Trail Blazers of the National Basketball Association. Yang Hansen was born on June 26, 2005 in Zibo, Shandong Province, and started playing basketball when he was a child. He joined the club for training in the third grade of elementary school and later enrolled in Zibo Sports School. Around 2020, at the invitation of Qingdao Guoxin Haitian Club, he entered the club's youth training system.

In 2021, the Qingdao Guoxin Haitian Youth Team defeated Tsinghua High School in the finals to win the U17 National Championship, and Yang Hansen was named the Best Defensive Player. In 2022, the Qingdao Guoxin Haitian Youth Team defended the U17 National Championship, and Yang Hansen was named the Most Valuable Player.

During the 2023â€“24 CBA season, Yang Hansen was promoted to the Qingdao Eagles' first team to play professional games. On October 23, 2023, he made his professional debut in the first round of the regular season against Beijing Enterprises. In the All-Star Game that season, Yang Hansen was selected as the starting player for the North Division Team. During his first season, NBA personnel visited the Qingdao training complex on multiple occasions to observe Yang Hansen , but he ultimately chose not to participate in the 2024 NBA draft. Yang Hansen was named both Rookie of the Year and Defensive Player of the Year after the season, after averaging 16.6 points, 10.5 rebounds and 3 assists.

Yang Hansen represented China at the 2023 FIBA Under-19 Basketball World Cup, averaging 12.6 points, 10.4 rebounds (3rd highest in the tournament), 4.7 assists (4th highest in the tournament) and 5 blocks (highest in the tournament), and was named in the All-Second Team. In February 2024, he made his national team debut in the 2025 FIBA Asian Cup qualifiers against Mongolia.
